W1D1: ??‍? Back to School ? 

Friday’s not so low key teacher work day was full of surprises and I am sure more will follow today with our virtual opening/ staff kickoff. Once we get in the swing of things I might feel better about #pandemic teaching; right now I am still in survival mode. 

So when my alarm ? went off, I decided to take Loki for a 30 minute shake out ??‍??(any other teachers get #firstdayjitters?! ??‍????) and while my legs felt good enough to run faster/ longer, the ole couch potato ?‍? did not... ? We still enjoyed the sunrise, cool temps and I’ll get a serious work out in at the lift lab this afternoon ??‍?? 

Good luck to all the teachers returning to school or already in their classrooms — this too shall pass ??

node.text:
Listen to the professionals. The ones who spent years qualifying. The ones who spent thousands TO qualify. The ones who have waded through hundreds and thousands of hours studying, being tested, revising and then using that knowledge on the hospital and lab floors, demonstrating that knowledge and expertise daily. Those who still, after qualifying and working in their field, continue to study, learn, and be tested, along side their job because that’s what their employment position REQUIRES of them; so to be up to date on medical knowledge and other related facts and theory, so to SAVE lives and function at the most basic level in their role. These are the individuals to listen to - not those who have a political agenda or other vested interests. Be smart ? make the best decisions for you and your family based on sound logic and your own research - not from blindly following the news (all of which are owned by the same small cluster of businesses), and individuals in government who can’t even string a sentence together. Get woke, stay in the know, listen to the qualified and the experienced ?
.
.
.
.
.

There are now less than two weeks to go before the Bright Ideas Challenge live pitch event. Time to polish up on your pitching techniques, your numbers, your understanding of revenues, expenses, and projected profits and everything else about your business. Know your business inside out, so you can awe our  panel of judges on the big day! Now the real work begins..! Comment your feelings below and If you would like to leave us a video of your answers, please do so and we will post our favourites to our channels.. Good luck

The Bright Ideas Challenge 2020 seeks to find and fund the launch of a minimum viable product to market. It is a live business pitch event for which submissions are open from the 21st June to 2nd Aug 2020. The challenge is open to 18 - 30 year olds in any of Africa's 54 nations and the live event takes place on the 30th of August 2020. It is ideal for those looking to realise the aspiration for business ownership and offers a cash prize and other start-up support, such as mentoring and developmental opportunities.

node.text:
A whole new world: five tips on managing mental health after quarantine ?

After the onset of a once in a lifetime global crisis, it would be an understatement to say that a huge number of people’s mental health has been impacted this year by the pandemic and subsequent fallout. As we have said previously, traumatic events like this can trigger a prolonged response from our fight or flight systems - this can result in too much exposure to stress hormones which can worsen our mental and physical health. It’s completely normal to be experiencing feelings of loneliness, anxiety, futility, and a loss in motivation. We recognise that many students returning this year might be concerned about managing their mental health as the pandemic continues.

It’s therefore more crucial than ever to take care of ourselves as much as possible. We have a few detailed suggestions on our website’s blog post (link in the bio) for those who might be feeling lost in where to start treating their mental health. ?

node.text:
Environment Breathes a Sigh of Relief in 2020!

Owing to the covid 19 lockdown, pollution levels in the atmosphere have been gradually reducing, waters are clearing and wildlife has been seen returning to their natural habitat. In some parts of the world, distant hills are coming into view once again as the veil of smoke is lifted from the skies. Energy consumption has also gone down at a large scale and commercial energy use has seen a decrease of nearly 30%. Overall, it appears that our environment is breathing a sigh of relief as human participation and activity have reduced.

These positive changes offer us an opportunity to reflect on our actions and their impact on the environment. They must encourage us to adopt a more holistic approach as me move forward and pave the way for a sustainable future.

node.text:
This is just a small fraction of animal abuse torture exploitation and death that you support, if you're not vegan. It happens every second of every minute of every hour in ways that most people are not aware of. But it is intentional,when you see animals as product or objects. It is time to let the animals enjoy their basic and fundamental rights, rights that are not ours to take from them.  Repost @whyyoueatinanimals_ @download.ins
---
This is an interesting and sad shipment of birds that arrived this morning at my place of employment in California all the way from my hometown of Janesville, Wisconsin. That’s where I was born and raised. This was a LONG DISTANCE these babies had to travel ??this world is just asking for another #pandemic ?? it’s going to be 100° today ? ? 
.
.
Every week, more than a billion live animals are transported worldwide over long distances, through blazing heat and freezing cold, often without food, water, or veterinary care—as if they were nothing more than freight. Their grueling journeys frequently end at a slaughterhouse, where they face a terrifying death. Others end up on pet store shelves or in laboratory cages.

On September 13, 2017, caring people around the world participate in a global day of action against all forms of live-animal transport. This day marks the anniversary of the world’s worst live-export disaster, when more than 67,000 sheep burned to death or drowned when the ship carrying them across the Indian Ocean burst into flames and sank.

The best way to help animals is never to buy them or their body parts for any reason, but we can also help reduce their suffering by taking action now to improve their transport conditions. 
.
.

Sinopsis :

Alive (2020) menceritakan tentang wabah misterius yang tiba-tiba menyebar di seluruh Kota Seoul dan dengan cepat berkembang di luar kendali.

Menegangkannya lagi, orang-orang yang bertahan terjebak di dalam apartemen mereka tanpa akses untuk data seluler, wifi, bahkan mengirim pesan ataupun membuat panggilan telepon.

Selain Yoo Ah In dan Park Shin Hye, film ini juga dibintangi Joon Woo dan Yoo Bin, dua orang penyintas yang terisolasi di tengah kota yang berbahaya.

Thank you for this message.  Life is a beautiful process of continued unfolding. ????

What you notice becomes your life. So notice it all – the joys, the problems and all of the pregnant spaces in between. None of us come into our lives and work fully formed. This means there is space for it all – what is obvious, less obvious, and hidden altogether; those “subtleties of life.” By noticing it all, we can be gifted in the right way – your way – with all the abundance such gifts bring.

This day 3 years ago, on my first solo backpacking trip around Europe, I was in Sicily as part of my journey throughout the top to bottom of Italy. It was in the small train station of the coastal city of Cefalù where I met 78 year old solo traveler, fellow Australian, and Vietnam War Veteran, John Auditore. He was revisiting Sicily, which he had visited many years ago. ⁣
⁣
As we both took the train back to Palermo, I got a brief glimpse into the incredibly varied and fascinating life of this stranger I had just met. He spoke of some of his life lessons, his travels, and about his family, who were back in Melbourne, Australia. He spoke little of his time in the military. ⁣
⁣
As it turns out, John had been grabbing his backpack and just going. Working odd jobs. Saving. Coming back to Australia. Leaving again. I saw some similarities with the current way I have been intentionally designing my life. ⁣
⁣
John had been traveling to far away places, with cultures and languages he never heard of, way back since the 70s and 80s. Many of these places are still considered off the beaten track today. He never stopped. ⁣
⁣
Just this year (3 years on) John was planning to solo travel through Pakistan because, why not see something extremely different? Then he planned to travel to various pockets around the world where he had friends waiting to see him. ⁣
⁣⁣⁣
Right now, he is on a strict lockdown in Melbourne, with family visiting to check up on him. John just gets on with it though, and sometimes we call to catch up. I will listen to his stories, and he will listen to my plans. ⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
Like mine (and probably yours), John's travel plans are on hold due to the current COVID-19 travel restrictions.⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣
What an amazing person to know. Do you know anyone a lot older than you that is still solo traveling?⁣⁣⁣ ?
⁣⁣.⁣

All the feels for the amazing pregnant mumma’s during this time ?

Shout out to all of the pregnant women adapting,growing and blooming in such difficult times. 
The happiest of pregnancies brings challenges and struggles so I can’t really image how it feels to be becoming a mother without your circle,your people,mother by your side throughout. 
You’re all doing so beautifully by the very fact you’re doing it. Your babies are growing and thriving blissfully unaware of all of the chaos that surrounds them. 
I’m sure some days just be so overwhelming and upsetting ? but you’re doing it and you’re doing an amazing thing at an extraordinarily difficult time. 
One day your kiddies will listen to the story of how they were born in absolute awe of the drama. They will wear it like a badge of honor that separates them from their siblings, another reason to feel special. I for one was always gagging for something to set me apart as a kid...praying for crutches daily ??? so no doubt they’ll love being able to tell their friends how strong they were to be born during a pandemic. 
One day this will just be a story you tell and perhaps it will feel like a dream,all a bit surreal. But you’ll see the other side of this,you’re strong and resilient...you’re a mother ?

You’re doing a wonderful job ?

Feel free to tag a friend who is expecting and send her some words of encouragement ??

#Repost @this_mama_doodles

node.text:
2020 Vision

This year has been rough. We've all been tested in ways we never imagined. We've washed our hands more than ever, donned face masks for the first time in daily life, and struggled with staying home and being away from our loved ones.

Sometimes it feels like this pandemic will never end. But we need to keep looking forward, because although our lives may be different in some ways forever, things will eventually get better.

My nephew keeps telling me on FaceTime that he wishes I could visit him. We live on opposite coasts, and although he understands why I cannot take my annual vacation to see him, it still hurts us both. I look forward to when we can all be vaccinated against this horrible virus so I can hug my little boy again.

What do you look forward to in our post-pandemic future?

?

P.S. My shoes are vegan leather.

Wacana pemasangan jaringan internet gratis untuk belajar siswa saat pandemi COVID-19 dikhawatirkan sejumlah masyarakat digunakan untuk bermain game online.

Adapun menyikapi kekhawatiran tersebut, Dinas Komunikasi dan Informatika (Diskominfo) Kota Tangerang akan membatasi penggunaannya hanya untuk waktu belajar. 

"Untuk akses game online dan situs terlarang kita sudah siapkan filternya, artinya sudah nggak bisa diakses," pungkas Kepala Diskominfo Kota Tangerang Mulyani, Minggu (16/8/2020).

Adapun progres program tersebut, saat ini sebanyak 946 rukun warga (RW) telah diverifikasi untuk dipasang jaringan internet. "Sudah, di RW non elite yang sudah kita verifikasi," ujarnya

Menurutnya, pemasangan jaringan internet tersebut akan dipasang di area publik setiap RW seperti di masjid dan balai warga. 

"Sehingga dimungkinkan anak-anak bisa dikendalikan secara protokol kesehatan COVID-19," katanya.

Ditargetkan jaringan internet ini dipasang pada awal September 2020. Dengan adanya jaringan internet ini diharapkan mampu membantu sistem pembelajaran daring bagi siswa. 

"Kita semua sedang berproses. Masih pengecekan lapangan," tuturnya.

node.text:
The NEET medical entrance exam and the Joint Entrance Examination (JEE) for admission into the IITs will be held as per schedule, the Supreme Court said today. "The careers of students cannot be put under jeopardy," the top court said as it dismissed a petition by 11 students to defer the exams due to the coronavirus crisis.

The two exams are scheduled to be conducted in September. "Life cannot be stopped. We have to move ahead with all safeguards and all... Are students ready to waste one whole year? Education should be opened up. Covid may continue for a year more. Are you going to wait another year? Do you know what the loss to the country and peril to the students is?," Justice Arun Mishra, who headed a three-judge bench of the Supreme Court said.

The 11 students from 11 states, who filed the petition, had wanted the authorities be asked to conduct the exams only after normalcy is restored. The students also sought to increase the number of examination centres for NEET and JEE across the country.

Alak Alok Srivastava, the lawyer who represented the students, argued that the students are looking to the top court for relief.

Solicitor General Tushar Mehta, who represented the National Testing Agency (NTA), informed the court that all safeguards will be taken for conducting the exams.

While the JEE is scheduled from September 1 to 6, the NEET exam is scheduled for September 13.

--- NDTV, Live Law

The most dangerous thing that's killing millions today staying at home is- STRESS!
.
Although invisible it can create havoc in our body and mind, changing the language of the chemicals running in our body. It's very important that we deal with it the right way.

In these testing times, it's very challenging to overcome our stress and remain sane.
.
Since most of us are now working from home  and will continue for another year at least, what can we do to avoid falling victim to this impending epidemic? How can we train our brains to focus on a single task? Here are a few ideas for creating a space and time free of distractions, to increase our chances of reaching a state of calmness.
.
Some simple tips and tricks, which we can easily achieve in our day to day life and I personally have started incorporating some of these.

1) Start your work session with a ritual you enjoy and end it with a reward.

2)Turn off your phone, if you have a task at hand, which is the most important task for you of the day
 OR
 you can also turn on the "do not disturb" function

This allows undivided attention and gets you to complete the work faster.

3)Read and respond to email only once or twice per day.

Define those times clearly and stick to them.

4) Try the Pomodoro Technique: Get yourself a kitchen timer and commit to working on a single task as long as it's running. The Pomodoro Technique recommends 25 minutes of work and 5 minutes of rest for each cycle, but you can also do 50 minutes of work and 10 minutes of rest. 

(Will do another post on how efficiently this works- But I work with this)

5) Bundle routine tasks-such as sending out invoices, making phone calls, and so on-and do them all at once.

6) Train your mind to return to the present when you find yourself getting distracted. Practice mindfulness or any other form of meditation.

7) Work in a space where you will not be distracted. If you find that your surroundings continue to distract you divide into groups of related tasks, and assign each group its own place and time. For example, if you're writing a magazine article, you could 
.

On a hamster wheel inside a glass box : 
"The whole concept of modern day human existence is so bizzare and more bizzare how most people never wake up to its absurdity. We keep on slaving at jobs we hate to buy uneccessary stuff and we never even question our desire for it. The futuristic dystopian society where there are overlords and workers who work even for food and water because the forests and the rivers are all owned and protected by the lords,  this society from a aldous huxley novel is not futuristic, we are living through it, enslavement of humanity was done long ago, we are all slaves, slave to the money, to shiny objects, to "lifestyle" , we keep on chasing something that we never really get to, the closer we get to it the further we are, like being on a hamster wheel inside a glass box. "

Thinking these thoughts I stopped to pick up a cherry scented candle on the way to the self check out counter.

node.text:
Environment Breathes a Sigh of Relief in 2020!

Owing to the covid 19 lockdown, pollution levels in the atmosphere have been gradually reducing, waters are clearing and wildlife has been seen returning to their natural habitat. In some parts of the world, distant hills are coming into view once again as the veil of smoke is lifted from the skies. Energy consumption has also gone down at a large scale and commercial energy use has seen a decrease of nearly 30%. Overall, it appears that our environment is breathing a sigh of relief as human participation and activity have reduced.

These positive changes offer us an opportunity to reflect on our actions and their impact on the environment. They must encourage us to adopt a more holistic approach as me move forward and pave the way for a sustainable future.

#environment #environmentbreathes #coronavirus #lockdown #emissions #climatechange #globalwarming #carbon #sustainableliving #sustainability #earth #pandemic #carbonemissions #energy #commerical #planetearth #savetheearth #reduceemissions

node.text:
Prior to the port explosion, Lebanon was in the midst of its worst economic crisis in history, with more than half of its 6 million people living near or below the poverty line, predominantly due to unshakeable corruption in the 'political elite'.⁠
⁠
This catastrophic disaster has now left as many as 300,000 people temporarily homeless and those injured or sick turning to overwhelmed and unequipped hospitals, as well as over 200 deaths and still many more missing.⁠
⁠
…Sadly, this suffering isn’t just limited to Lebanon. Globally, this pandemic, amongst everything else that has hit in 2020, has amplified the impact of the poverty cycle and the fallout of disasters (both natural and induced by humanity).⁠
⁠
As devastating as this is, it’s absolutely not a time to just put our heads in the sand, and we recognise the courage required to keep it up. It’s crucial now, as ever, that we’re being innovative and proactive in tackling these social issues using sustainable strategies for long-term good. ⁠
⁠
If you’re looking for some actionable ways to support Lebanon right now, here are some accounts we recommend checking out: @lebaneseredcross @impact.lebanon @lebfoodbank⁠
.⁠
.⁠
.⁠
#Lebanon #stateoftheworld #poverty #pandemic #disaster #globalIssues #sustainabledevelopment #socialenterprise

I was 12 when I worked on my first film. Casting approached me at school, took a polaroid, and asked for my father’s phone number. He said no immediately. ⁣
⁣
Casting called back the next day and asked if my father would change his mind. The principal even got involved. ⁣
⁣
Did I mention this was for featured extra work? I had no idea what that meant at the time, but now I know how unprecedented all  of that was. How many times are we up for major speaking roles only to lose it to someone else on the smallest of technicalities? #DivineIntervention at work. ⁣
My parents eventually said yes. My dad said no more movies until after I turned 18, and at the time I didn’t care. I was just way too excited to finally have something no one else could compare me against. In just over a decade of living, I was already sick of hearing that I wasn’t particularly obedient, my grades weren’t good, I wasn’t that great at piano, I was gaining weight, etc. ⁣
⁣
My saving grace would be to hopefully marry well. I’m still hearing this, decades later. I had the time of my life on that set. I earned my #SAG vouchers. Then I forgot all about acting and tried my hardest to turn myself into a “good Asian kid,” because I was sick of hearing that I would never make the cut. ⁣
⁣
Divine intervention again. I worked myself into such a state that my mental health completely dissolved. I almost didn’t graduate high school, but one day I convinced my mom to take me to an open call, and soon afterwards I was begging my father to let me start acting lessons. I hadn’t turned 18 yet. ⁣
⁣
My entire adult life has either been working to be able to move to LA, or working to be able to stay out here, which was completely separate from me growing as an artist and navigating one of the toughest industries out there. It was finally early this year, after well over a decade of the #hustle, when the elusive “shift” happened and I was able to focus more on being an artist and less on basic survival. ⁣
⁣
#Pandemic or no, I hope I can save someone out there a lot of time and heartache.⁣
⁣
You’ve got absolutely nothing to prove.⁣
Shut out all that noise & just live your life. ⁣
⁣
Xo?

node.text:
Today, we are thinking about the craftsmen, small business owners and people who produce local delicious products.
We are thinking how hard it must be to carry on, how difficult it is to survive, not only the pandemic, but also the economic crisis in Lebanon. To top it all off, The 4th of August came unexpectedly to ruin their last hope. We’ve worked with many craftsmen due to our engagement in the non governmental sector and came close to their realities and aspirations. 
Have we thought about buying their local products? First of all because they’r good for our health, competitive in terms of pricing especially with the market going crazy and the imported products but last and not least to support them, give them hope, praise their goods and encourage them to feed us miracles. 
These people sweat constantly to preserve their dignity and provide a decent life for their families. 
Today We worry about them the most. Today We choose them, with agony, among all sufferings. Because they will continue to suffer in pride and dignity. 
.
.
.
#craftmanship #beirutlebanon #pandemic #explosion

node.text:
“Sarmad Book Five: Home” is out!
.
Eric Patel
.
I've been feeling too tired and angry to make sense of what's going on in the world lately. Amidst the pandemic, through the horrors of a genocidal police state and racial disparities in access to healthcare and food, white supremacy continues to prove it was never safe to leave home or be at home in the U.S. for the other. What would home look like if instead of fetishizing assimilation and death, it activates life, difference and understanding? In this piece, I use personal citations or bibliography as a way to begin working through a portrait of home that's not there.
.
Eric Patel is an artist, educator and organizer based in Harlem, New York
.

node.text:
NEW DELHI:
The Supreme Court rejected the plea seeking postponement of NEET and JEE examinations 2020.A three-judge bench headed by Justice Arun Mishra said that 'life has to go on' despite Covid and the court cannot put career of students in peril by interfering with the decision of the National Testing Agency.
Petitioner's lawyer Alakh Alok Srivastava said that vaccine for Covid is 'on its way' and he is not seeking an indefinite postponement of the exams.
'Career of students cannot be put in peril.We find no merit in the petition.The petition is dismissed', the bench which also comprised justices BR Gavai and Krishna Murari said.
'You (lawyers) have demanded opening of physical courts.But you want exams to be postponed. Postponment of exams is a loss for country,' the bench said.
The way our honourable judges are comparing exams with court is really ridiculous.
Few days ago Schools were reopened in USA and it proved to be hazardous.Many students along with teachers were later tested Positive.

node.text:
I dare to say that this year is not what I expected it to be. The pandemic has really thrown a curveball. Many of us have experienced some degree of loss. 

Although loss is often linked with death, this is not the only loss people experience. The degree of loss people experience may vary, but the pain the individual experiences is still very much real. 

A loss causes us to have to look inwardly and if not careful can cause you to start questioning yourself. 

Making sure that you have the right perspective can help in moving forward. 

Define your loss and give yourself the space to go through the process of grieving your loss. 

Note that the way you grieve a loss is uniquely yours and yours alone. There is no “right way” to grieve a loss.

I once read the following  metaphor on grief:

Grief can be like a deep and fresh wound. You feel intense pain, but that's part of your body's healing process. Without the pain, you might ignore the wound and let it fester.

As time passes, the wound slowly heals, and turns into a scar. This is integrated grief. The deep wound has closed, but the scar will always be there, raw to the touch.

However, sometimes our wounds become infected and fail to heal. This is complicated grief. The wound continues to cause immense pain, and only seems to get worse. At this point, professional help may be needed.

Note that the pain as horrible as it might feel is part of the healing process. So as much as you may want to try to avoid it, I would urge you to lean into it. Otherwise your body will find ways to release that negative energy, typically through body ailments like headaches, stomaches, and backaches to name a few. 

Below are some signs that would let you know  that professional help may be needed: 
* Are unable to feel any positive emotion
* Feelings of sadness are constant and not decreasing 
* Experiencing poor self esteem and self loathing
* Feelings of worthlessness

node.text:
Algeria launched Islamic finance products in a bid to attract money from the informal market, but bankers warn it will take more to fix the country's struggling economy.

According to Abderahmane Benkhalfa, a former minister of finance and ex-head of the banking association, Algeria hopes to tap into the significant revenues of the informal market, estimated to be as much as $30-35 billion.

"It is not only necessary to draw these resources, but to inject them into banks in order to bolster the economy," Benkhalfa said.

The North African country’s economy has been battered by falling oil prices and the coronavirus pandemic, triggering alarm bells among officials and experts.

The International Monetary Fund (IMF) forecast that Algeria's economy will shrink 5.2 percent this year.

Earlier this month, state-run National Bank of Algeria offered nine Islamic financial services, receiving a certificate from Muslim clerics ensuring they were compatible with Islamic law.

But Benkhalfa, who is also a member of a panel of African experts tasked by the African Union to mobilize international funds to help the continent combat coronavirus, warned that Islamic finance is not a "miracle solution.” 

In Algeria, Africa's largest nation and home to 43 million people, most transactions are done in cash circulating outside the formal banking sector, said Professor Mohamed Boudjelal, an expert on Islamic finance.

Many Algerians "turn their nose up" at conventional banking, Boudjelal said.

Some Muslims believe that the traditional banking system is incompatible with their faith.

Islamic finance -- the provision of financial services in accordance with religious laws -- is a fast growing sector which has been adopted in many Muslim countries.

The industry is based on shared profit and loss, while earning interest is banned as "usury.” 

Funds are also blocked from investing in companies associated with tobacco, alcohol, pork or gambling.#s63

After almost a week without rain here in Edinburgh ?, today Monday 17th of August and almost 2 months ago this Instagram page where I show and speak of Scotland at this stage more even of Edinburgh and where I also make myself known talking about me  and what it's like to be an immigrant.  At this stage everything is strange, with this pandemic situation that makes no one comfortable and at the same time leaves us limited in so much.  This page started at the time of the lockdown and when I returned to Edinburgh after 1 and a half months in Portugal on vacation and my family ?, as the pandemic closed the city completely and the world I chose to go to Portugal to pass  one days.  When I returned on June 21st and after a trip of more than a day with a stopover in London of more than 24 hours h I was waiting for the bus to go home and in conversation with a friend the idea came up:
 -What if I created an Instagram page to show Scotland to my eyes.  And so it was, and here we are almost two months later, but you know, I feel such a pleasure to use this IG page as I never used it.  I got to know the streets and the city better, I returned to feel the pleasure that I didn’t feel in a few years, that is to do photography, I leave my house to take photographs, I walk for hours and hours in the city and see all the corners that  you can give me a photo to show you (and there are so many) I love Edinburgh.  I can't get enough of this one bit.
 But you who are on this side and accompany me here whenever possible, or with comments, questions, suggestions, likes etc etc etc. I thank you from the heart because all the pleasure is also in this feedback that I have almost daily from all of you.
 Always welcome here, I will always be here.
 To thank all those people who know that they are really important in my life and without having to say who they are because they really know who they are, and I really love them.
 Thanks again for being on that side.
 A good day, a good week and see you here.

 Manuel Vieira is my name.

Let me give you one better. When a person gets infected, he either recovers or he dies OR he stays ill. Factor in the 'stays ill' part and we will know where we are headed.

In a statement released on August 12, the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare claimed India’s “high” COVID-19 recovery rate was the result of a successful implementation of its containment strategy. On the same day, India’s recovery rate crossed 70%, and as on August 17 morning stood at 71.91%.

However, the rate of recoveries is a poor, if not meaningless, measure of a country’s response to its COVID-19 epidemic. This is simply because the recovery rate naturally increases during the course of an epidemic or pandemic. If a person gets COVID-19, only two things can happen: they recover or they die. So as more and more people fall sick with COVID-19, i.e. as the epidemic progresses, more and more people will also recover or die over time.

At the end of the pandemic, the recovery rate has to be 100% minus the given population’s infection fatality rate. If this rate is, say, 3%, the final recovery rate will be 97%. The fundamental point is that from the epidemic’s start to finish, this figure will slowly increase from 0% to 97% – even if we don’t intervene.

A new strain of the novel coronavirus called 'D614G', deemed ten times more infectious, has been detected in Malaysia, said Director General of Health Noor Hisham Abdullah in a Facebook post on Saturday.

Abdullah said that this meant people needed to be more aware and careful in the country. The mutation infects other individuals 10 times more and spreads more easily by an individual 'super spreader', he said

The mutation has been spotted in three cases from a cluster which started when a restaurant owner and permanent resident returned to the country from India. It has also been detected in another cluster case which started with returnees from the Philippines.
(Representative image)
Story via: @cnnnews18

node.text:
‪‘Humans of Space’ is now officially LIVE on @Spotify @ApplePodcasts and other podcast host sites! 
-
-
A show that explores #curiosity & #space. A new episode every week, produced at Ox4 Sound Studios, I chat with people who I’ve met along the way who have taken the road less travelled. People who are brave & bold & can help us understand what it takes to live a life that we truly want. The first two episodes with @canadianspaceagency’s retired #astronaut, doctor & engineer Robert Thirsk, and @hi_seas director & astrobiologist @astro_michaela, launch the new podcast, with a new episode up every Monday morning.
-
-
I’m not going to lie, this lockdown has made my job of sharing human stories of #space, #science & #sustainability tough. I’ve spent the summer figuring out how I can continue. Most of us freelancers & involved in #cultural & #arts activities have had our work come to a near standstill. We have struggled & had to really think about how to move forward as the world recovers from a pandemic. And if ever there was a time for cultural & arts activities, now is that time. 
-
-
This podcast is my way of continuing my job through #lockdown, along with a web series for families called #GalaxySquad, some upcoming livestream events and lots of chats with our young citizens across the planet. I’ve set up a @Patreon page if people can afford to support my work (from €1.99/month). 
-
I will continue to make #space & #STEM content during #lockdown and beyond. Let’s stay positive! 
-
I’m happy to share what I’ve learned this summer with anyone who is struggling at the moment with making their work. We can all support each other. 
-
-
So please check out HUMANS OF SPACE on Spotify & Apple Podcasts & be inspired to Dream Big, work hard, have a plan & just walk forward.

Dalam rangka memperingati HUT RI ke 75
hari ini, setiap tahun rutinitas ke Asia Afrika  Bandung buat photo-photo dengan nuansa bendera #merahputih yang berkibar megah.

dan karna masa #pandemic harus stay save.. jalankan protokol pake masker.

Sejak #viruscorona mewabah hampir di seluruh dunia, banyak orang yang terkena dampak baik dari ekonomi dan juga semua anak Indonesia yang harus PJJ ( Pembelajaran Jarak Jauh ).

sedih rasanya, pasti banyak keluhan yang pengen ke skolah kangen temen2, guru dan main ke mall, ke tempat wisata tapi sejak new normal tetap kita harus waspada, nah kimmy ingin menghibur orang dengan #magicstreet buat temen2 yang sedang asyik berfoto dan nongkrong di sepanjang Jalan Asia Afrika.

juga membagikan masker @kimwardrobe
buat temen2 agar selalu ingat pake masker dan rajin cuci tangan.

semoga hal kecil dan kegiatan positive kimmy ini bisa jadi memotivasi agar kita semua bersatu bersama memutuskan rantai penyebaran #covid19 dan Indonesia bangkit, sembuh dan semua orang tidak terpuruk berkelanjutan baik dari aspek ekonomi dan pekerja yang dirumahkan dll. . semngat.. Merdeka!

node.text:
Sudah pernah kuceritakan, ada makhluk yang terus-menerus bergelantungan di dadaku. Pelan-pelan menggerogoti warasku, diam-diam mempengaruhi keputusan-keputusanku; adalah kamu.

Perempuan yang senang sekali membuyarkan mimpi lelaki rapuh dan terlihat lugu. Perempuan yang gemar sekali membayang-bayangi langkah dan merubahnya menjadi ragu.

Setan dan kawanannya telah lama ku usir dari tubuhku, sedangkan kamu seolah malas untuk pergi.
Hingga kini, tak lagi mampu kupungkiri — bagiku, jiwa ini tak lagi terasa seperti rumah sendiri.
------------------------- #tJOEplikan
Sketch by @denyjoe_ @dearstudios

node.text: @my_new_danish_life same here!! but let’s keep@the spirit ?
Everyone I know is back to work in DK, and I’m even back to the classroom. I have a feeling that things may change at any point though. So hard to tell the future during these times!
@lauraendinamarca I want to be working from home, and when I say home is Mexico ???
@unamexicanaendinamarca thqt was my plan in march, work from México 1 month

I work 100% from home. The company I am working with have had this model, since they started in the 90's. So it was kind of strange for them to have an office in Europe. One of the owners was living in a boat with his wife, traveling the wold while working.
@free_thetraveler yes, nothing like before. For the I feel the bond I created with some of my colleagues for the last 3 yrs just vanished in 5 months of isolation.

I am still in hjælpepakke, I will finally be back to work on the 31st of August. There will be a lot of changes tho, and in our department we will need to decide who will work from home and who will be working from the office. So it won't be like before ?
For your sake, I hope things change soon ?. Best of luck ?!
@unamexicanaendinamarca thqt was my plan in march, work from México 1 month

Working from home is the new set up in the company where I work. As we are now back to phase 1 in DK , it is still not mandatory since March to go to the office, only business critical. ???‍???‍??

I love that the work I do can be done located everywhere, at the office, at home or in the beach. 
But I do miss the office ?interaction, my daily office dress-code and the good morning talks in Danish with the lady from the canteen while i’m ordering my vegan latte. I’m the girl who gets the energy from others and definitely i look forward to share lunch again and to have random talks at the coffee machine. 

I value more each of my colleagues, my Manager ,my desk, my work. Definitely we are way to far to succeed with this pandemic but for sure I can say - I’m so happy and proud of my work and for the opportunities in Denmark despite this situation. 

How is the situation in your work place? 

#workingfromhome  #workingfromeverywhere #Danmark #homeoffice #expat #expatindenmark #expatlife #pandemic #2020

node.text:
#Repost @houseofpebblesorg
• • • • • •
Live Session Today on Facebook!

Today at 8pm, you would be meeting Basit Bhojani, Clinical Psychologist and Ariba Omer, a student of Psychology Majors.

In this session we will be talking about social pressures faced by men in our society and culture. The discussion will be focused on the idea of masculinity that is ingrained in the society. Additionally we will be talking about the challenges this emotional repression can pose for men i.e. negative and positive coping mechanisms.
Furthermore, in conversation with Mr. Basit Bhojani we want to delve into specific situations where men find emotional catharsis and how that helps them regulate their emotions.

Mohammad Basit Bhojani is a clinical psychologist, certified career counselor & a professional trainer. He completed his education in the field of clinical psychology from Institute of professional Psychology. He currently works at Karwan-e-hayat and Careforhealth as a practitioner and counselor.
 
Join us, we would love to know your thoughts.

Official UK government figures released last week show that the number of people in employment across Britain has suffered its biggest decline since 2009, dropping by around 220,000 in the three-month period since June, with the self-employed reportedly being hardest hit. Analysts now fear that the COVID-19 outbreak and subsequent lockdowns will begin to take a heavier toll on the labour market as the government winds down its huge job-protection scheme, with an unemployment rate of 7.5% now looking possible before the end of the year.

TRIBUNSUMSEL.COM, MUARAENIM-Fedrik Adhar, Jaksa yang pernah menangani kasus Ahok dan Kasus Novel Baswedan, meninggal dunia, Senin (17/8/2020).

Hal ini dibenarkan oleh Abu Nawas, seorang jaksa yang pernah menjadi rekan kerjanya sesama bertugas di Kajari Muaraenim beberapa tahun yang lalu saat dikonfirmasi Tribunsumsel.com melalui sambungan selulernya, Senin (17/8/2020).

"Ya benar, kami mendapat kabar, bahwa Fedrik baru saja meninggal dunia sekitar setengah jam yang lalu,"katanya.

Dikatakan Abu,bahwa Sebelum meninggal dunia, Jaksa Fedrik baru pulang dari Baturaja, Sumsel, karena ada urusan keluarga.

"Infonya setelah pulang dari Baturaja, Fedrik mendadak sakit, dilarikan ke rumah sakit, dan sempat dirawat, hingga kami memdengar berita duka ini setengah jam yang lalu bahwa Fedrik meninggal dunia,"katanya.

Namun lanjutnya pihaknya belum mengetahui penyakit apa yang diderita fedrik.

"Untuk sakit apa,itu kita belum tau,karena kita juga baru dapat kabar bahwa fedrik meninggal,"ungkapnya.

.

According to a report, while the world attempts to deal with the COVID-19 pandemic caused by the SARS-CoV-2, Malaysia has detected a new strain of the novel coronavirus that’s found to be 10 times more infectious.

Anthony Fauci, America’s top infectious disease expert, has warned that the SARS-CoV-2 virus was showing some signs of mutation in a way that may speed the spread of the virus.

The mutation - called D614G -was found in at least three of the 45 cases in a cluster that started from a restaurant owner. The man, who returned from India and intruded his 14-day home quarantine, has since been sentenced to five months in prison.

Director-General of Health Noor Hisham Abdullah said, the strain could mean that existing studies on vaccines may be incomplete against the mutation. The country confirmed 26 new cases on Saturday, the most since July 28, and added 25 cases on Sunday.

Story by @subhosmitaaa

V I T A M I N  D 

Sharing this concise information from one of our stockists and a practitioner whom we highly respect - Thanks Steph ?

#Repost from @thenaturalnutritionist 
???
I’ve received lots of questions about vitamin D, especially since the following study was released earlier this week: Low plasma 25(OH) vitamin D level is associated with increased risk of COVID‐19 infection: an Israeli population‐based study (DOI: doi:10.1111/febs.15495).

The main finding was that low vitamin D status is an independent risk factor for COVID-19. It is also well known that vitamin D has potent anti-viral properties including reduced pro-inflammatory cytokine production, which is protective in diseases that cause a cytokine storm (i.e. COVID-19).

Great food sources of vitamin D are wild caught salmon, tuna and sardines, cod liver oil, egg yolks and mushrooms. It is however important to remember that we often don’t get enough vitamin D from food. While wild caught salmon provides just shy of 1000IU in 100g and one egg yolk 37IU, it’s what we consume daily that counts.

Vitamin D really is a hormone that our bodies produce when exposed to sunlight. And many of us are deficient, for reasons including increased indoor time [hello COVID], over application of ‘slip, slop, slap’, or dark skin which has increased melanin, a pigment that lowers the skin’s ability to make vitamin D.

While sunlight is the preferred option, supplementation can be extremely helpful, especially during winter months and periods of isolation [hello Victoria].

I don’t recommend Ostelin as it is often poorly absorbed. Two products you can access quite easily are:
* Adults: Bioceuticals D3 + K2 Spray
* Children: Brauer Kids Liquid Vitamin D

So how much do you take? Well, it depends. In an ideal world you would test your vitamin D levels, aiming for an optimal level of 100-150 mmol/L (40-60 ng/mL). Most often I see 1000IU has been prescribed, as our RDA is so low. However, RDAs are designed to keep us alive [just] and in this case, avoid conditions such as rickets, but RDAs rarely achieve optimal health. Keep in mind that for most adults, 1000IU is rarely enough.

How well has attempts by alternative remedies worked in dealing with the corona virus? Does it really work? What is the evidence for its efficacy? 

Traditionally India is a country that has two indigenous healthcare systems – Siddha & Ayurveda and a third adopted more recent Unani with roots in Perso-Arabic traditional medicine as practiced in Mughal India and in Muslim culture. All three systems primarily use plant-based ingredients to formulate their concoctions. In addition to plants they also use metals, minerals and ingredients of animal origin like fat, meat, bone, urine and excreta. All three systems presuppose the presence, in the body, of different “humours”. And they believe all illnesses are a result of an imbalance in these humours. In both Ayurveda and Siddha there are three humours (doshas) – V?ta (Gas) – The Air Humour, Pitta (Bile) – The Fire Humour and Kapha (Phlegm) – The Water Humour. Unani on the other hand has four humours blood, phlegm, yellow bile and black bile – a concept that originates from the Greek humour theory of Hippocrates.

node.text:
"If we want to Unite, we must let go, of being Right"
Right now there is so much confusion, distraction, disempowerment, fear, hatred and judgement being thrown together in a cleverly packaged device. 
That has us believing we are "educating ourselves", "waking up", "stepping away from conformity". 
All the whilst being sheep to the same things, on the same platforms, we say we are against. 
Still spending our time filling our mind's with thoughts of those we want to see out of power, whilst giving them our power. 
Through our time, our thoughts, our anger, and we take away from our own power, our time, our passions, our purpose, our ideas. 
Which is perfect, as then we can stay asleep, if not comatosed, to the reality WE are experiencing. To what we care about, and we simply continue to feed the corrupt and the greedy without admitting or seeing it. 
Whether our energy is focused on the idea, theories, celebrities, governments, corporations, global pandemics (including everything from starvation to obesity, poverty to greed, depression to oppression, being disillusioned to being "awake", deceit to honesty, homelessness to kidnapping) from a space of "support", "educating", "being positive", or from "exposing" and "knowing whats going on", we are still focused on them. Not ourselves. 
We say we want to create a new world, yet how can we do this if we are only looking at the old one?
What does the information you are attaching to really do for you?
How does it impact your life? 
How is it relevant to the direction of your path? 
Even if you were to know the "truth" what does that then change in your life? 
What are the thoughts you have of the world when you learn it?
What energy are you putting out? Honestly? 
Love? Or fear? 
Truth or righteousness? 
Clarity or confusion? 
Empowerment or disempowerment? 
What is your true intention in "knowing it all"?

China's vaccine maker CanSino Biologics Inc has won a patent approval from Beijing for its COVID-19 vaccinecandidate Ad5-nCOV, People's Dailyreported, citing documents from the country's intellectual property regulator. The patent was submitted for application on March 18, and was approved on August 11, the report said. It is the first COVID-19 vaccine patent granted by China.

China's CanSino's vaccine uses a modified common cold virus to carry genetic material from the new coronavirus into the human body, a method also used by the Oxford/AstraZeneca vaccine.

Source: https://www.livemint.com/science/health/china-grants-its-first-vaccine-patent-to-cansino-report-11597644562627.html

node.text:
Can #Indian #businesses not only survive the #pandemic, but also turn the crisis into a growth opportunity?
Not all sectors of the economy suffer equally in times of hardship, as one sector's loss may be another sector's gain.
This is true of #India's #economy in the wake of the #COVID-19 pandemic: although the #lockdowns initially shocked almost all #sectors, some are experiencing a quicker recovery than others. And, still other sectors—as we shall see in the following—may even end up profiting from the fight against #COVID19.

Our very first speaker for this webinar is Mr Shivam, @shivamnow who is an author and an certified emotional intelligence life coach. He is very well trained and experienced in this field. He has been helping people to live a better life through his approach, across the world.
